segments.text: Yes, she has been living in Austin for about 15 or 20 years.
Does she have a husband in Austin?
She is living with a son who lives in Austin.
She has a son and a granddaughter.
Y una hija que vivía en Austin pero ya se fue.
Y tengo otra hermana que vive en Lobo.
Ella tiene como 20 años de vida.
Y son todos los hermanos que tengo.
Y todos sus hermanos vivían aquí en los Estados Unidos.
Ahorita tengo nomás tres hermanos vivos.
And his mother lived here, but his father died in Mexico.
He died many years before his family came here to Texas, right?
Yes, well, my mother used to talk
I was 4 years old when he died.
He died here in General Treviño.
I was talking to my mother that he was dead.
I think they didn't have a lot of money to get a doctor or a hospital.
Life was difficult in those days.
It was difficult for the people who lived there.
I think it's still very difficult for many people.
For example, when you have a sick person, well...
I think there are many very poor people who... who can barely afford to eat during the day.
But here, are there people who live here who don't have enough to eat?
Here, the people who don't have enough to eat are the ones who don't want to work.
Because there is a lot of work anywhere.
And the people who don't have enough to eat are the ones who don't want to work.
And here it's also expensive, well, but...
It's because either the wife or the children don't want to work.
Because here there is a lot of work for any person, be it a man or a woman.
Right now it's a bit expensive here, but as it were, you can eat.
Is the opportunity for education good here?
People who have money to continue their studies, it's good.
Poor people can't go to school or finish school because they are very poor.
The father has to get the children out of school so that they can go to work, so that he can help them to maintain all the families.
Well, it's a problem here too.
Yes, but here they have a much better chance.
¿Conoce otros parques de los Estados Unidos?
No, there are only wolves pecking at the cotton once or twice.
But some people here go to... Oh yes, they go to California and other states.
Why don't you go to these other parts?
I don't like to go there and there and there.
Because here I am working with these ladies.
Here I work as if it were mine.
I leave here in the morning with my little truck.
I'm going to do whatever I want, as if it were mine.
If they have another job, they do it.
But I don't come to ask them in the mornings here, what job am I going to do now?
But I go out there, I do anything there.
There is a country to break there.
And I've had this job for many years, I think.
It's a house for you, a house of many years, yes.
Well, your wife was from a ranch near here, correct?
And she was born in Mexico or in Mexico as well?
Yes, she was born in Mexico.
When did she come to the United States?
Well, I think the reason is that they came to look for life to have a better time, I think.
They are poor people from Zacatecas.
From the city of Zacatecas, or a ranch in the state.
I think it's a ranch, but it's called Zacatecas because it's the same state.
It's a city, Zacatecas, and it's the state.
And the state, I think they lived in a ranch, I think.
And they didn't come because of the revolution?
I don't know the life of them correctly.
Do you know anyone who came here because of the revolution?
No one says this is the reason for coming to Texas.
When I came here to live here, all those people were already living here.
And all those people, the older ones, we came with the uncle from Concire, a ranch that the uncle had.
They told me that this is how the ranch is called.
That's where the uncle came from.
And that's where a lot of men came to work here with him.
They were working with him in the ranch.
And those men were already here working for when I came.
a reason for a better life.
that I know come to this country because of the revolution.
Yes, some because they tell me that the soldiers come to their town and make war in the town and things like that.
And for this reason they came here.
I've heard that when a bunch of soldiers came to a village, they collected all the food for them, for the soldiers.
Food and corn for the horses and all that.
I think that's why many came here.
There were many places where I think I've heard other older people talk.
That many times they took people and put them in as soldiers.
I think for that reason many came here.
And they who came for this reason, do they spend all their lives here or did they return to Mexico after the Revolution?
Well, I think that when the Revolution ended, I think that many of them returned there and others stayed here, I think.
Many young people, I think, got married here and I think they stayed here.
The older ones would come back, I think, again.
They would have their little house there, little animals that they had in the ranch, or something like that, right?
That's why they would come back, I think.
And the younger ones, well, I think they became...
I think some of them got married and stayed here.
It's partly a matter of heart.
The older ones have more heart in medicine.
They have more head to go back, thinking about what they left there.
No, no, no, no piensa mucho en regresar por lo que dejaron allá los papás.
Mayormente si se casa aquí, bueno, ya disimula un poco de lo que tienen allá, dejan allá.
Sí, yo creo es la verdad.
Y ellos que vienen, que estaban ricos, ¿están diferentes de los pobres?
¿Qué son las diferencias entre los ricos y los pobres aquí en los Estados Unidos?
Well, I can't speak very bad of them either.
Because the rich have their money.
And the poor, well, they spend it with the little they earn.
And in Mexico it's the same.
Well, thank you very much for... Well, thank you very much, ma'am.
It's been a pleasure to meet you.
